background=http://www.cafenet.plus.com/The_Magicians_Tower/Images/Background_1.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://www.cafenet.plus.com/The_Magicians_Tower/Images/Background_1.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=blumfield>blumfield</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#333333>(12/19/02 3:26:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=61>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: First off...</span><hr size=1> Cerios writes:  &quot;The fact that socialism is often viewed as a middle ground between the two further shows the stupidity of your initial definition.&quot;<br>
<br>
That it's commonly viewed as a middle ground between the two isn't in dispute.  That it's a predictable developmental stage of history, which naturally precedes and follows other such stages, is hogwash.  The latter is what the definition asserted.<br>
<br>
I will not respond to the ad hominem portions of your post.<br>
<br>
Cerios:<br>
<br>
&quot;This actually reminds me of when I was young and I was having a debate with an uncle of mine, and he was saying how mad it made him that people were stealing from his store, because it meant that the store would have to raise its prices. I being about 10 years old at the time asked him why that was, as he tried to explain to me that if the store was to stay in buisness that they would have to raise there prices to maintain there profitability thereby costing all the honest consumers more. Well by this point anyone with half a brain listening to him would have understood the stupidity of his argument but to him the logic was simple straight forward and definitly had never actually been thought threw. &quot;<br>
<br>
Ok, I'll bite -- your uncle's argument is sound.  He has X amount of product which he sells for a certain amount to maintain profitability.  If his stock is reduced unexpectedly because it's stolen, he has to charge more for the remaining stock to maintain profitability.  What the heck is stupid about that?<br>
<br>
Cerios:<br>
<br>
&quot;As to your last point, the inefficenicies of goverment, its quite obvious you don't really have any idea what your talking about when it comes to the mechanics of goverments. Dollar for dollar goverments are without a doubt far more efficent then even the most efficent capitalist orginizations of any real size and are far less prone to corruption.&quot;<br>
<br>
You have not posted any data to support this claim.  In fact, the long term inefficiency of state run business is well documented.  A state run business does not *need* to be efficient, it needs only to provide the basic minimum of service to continue.  A business competing with other businesses, on the other hand, must necessarily outperform other businesses or it will go under.  It's a question of necessity.<br>
<br>
The fact is that the capitalist consumer has real power to influence efficiency:  he chooses, with his pocketbook, what sort of business is rewarded and what sort is not.  With every purchase he determines which business stays afloat and which sinks.  <br>
<br>
Conversely, the consumer in the position of dealing with a socialised business (which does not compete with others) is weak.  If he is dissatisfied with the way the business is run, he must whine to those in charge, hoping they'll see it his way.  He is reduced to the status of a child begging favours of a parent.<br>
<br>
bleh<br>
<br>
blumfield <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=falkahnhan>Falkahnhan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#333333>(12/20/02 7:06:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   skipped everything but the first post...</span><hr size=1> I skipped pretty much everything but the first post, but I wanted to toss in my 2cp about socialistic health care.  The trade off comes between spending money and getting rapid service.  In the US we have a healthcare system where if you don't have money you don't get service, but if you have money you get service and usually very quickly.  If you look at Canada, a country with a more socialistic healthcare system, yes everyone is covered, but instead of getting seen by a doctor right away you may be waiting a week or two or more to be seen.  Also Canada is running into the problem of doctors refusing to perform medical procedures becuase the clinics/offices/hospitals are doing nothing but losing money because everyone is entitled to healthcare.  So what good is a bankrupt healthcare system that can't provide support to anyone.  <br>
The idea of socialism, as with communism, is good on paper but when applied to the real world it falls apart.  The largest problems with giving away something like healthcare to everyone when not everyone can afford it is that 1.) you have an unequal distribution of the burden of payment, or 2.) you have a system that's giving out more money in healthcare than it's taking in.  Personally I don't like the idea of my money going to pay for someone elses drugs, so option 1 is out.  As for option 2... well the problems with that can be seen in Canada.  The basis of &quot;universal&quot; healthcare, just like social security, is that you have more people paying into it than people using it and this will only work for a time.  <br>
<br>
Falkahnhan<br>
