<br>
I assume most of the people that posted here are american, which I am not. I am danish, so the comment may be flavored by looking over the pond.<br>
<br>
The american political system is dominated by the two big parties, republicans and democrats. I know that people occational try to start some other parties or run as individuals, but are usually not very successful in getting much support. So, because you have the two parties, if you are not a republican, then you must be a democrat. It is a bit two-dimentional. If this is how it usually works, it is easy to transfer this to other things. Neither the republican party or the democratic party has much in common with a comunist. So, because USSR for a long time was the enemy, was comunist and used socialism as a way to run the country, and because USA was 'the good guys', wasn't comunist and used capitalism as a way to run the country it is easy to say that comunism = socialism. This is not correct, but comunism has often embraced socialism.<br>
<br>
I myself is used to a lot of political parties and so are a lot of european countries. It has happend that one political party has had absolute majority but only very rarely so. What most often happen is that the goverment ends up consisting of a coalision of parties, with a bias towards either right wing or left wing. It has also happend that even minor political parties has gotten a significant influence on the politics run by the goverment.<br>
<br>
What I ment to say with this is, that it is all shades of grey and there are more poles in the system than just capitalism, socialism, comunism and so on.<br>
<br>
