 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=silverbladetheenchanter>Silverblade the Enchanter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magi Draconis</span><br>  Posts: 2272<br> <font color=#333333>(1/25/03 5:29:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=79>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.silverblades-suitcase.com/artofadreamer/3d/excaliburthumb1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Idiot capitalists</span><hr size=1> Caenn,<br>
<br>
Know, I &quot;demonize&quot; the despicable idea that money &gt;&gt;&gt; people. Capitolism is merely an econimic tool, but like almost anything people do they take it to extremes. Religion, politics etc. I have heard people argue that it IS right that people should get favoured medical treatment because they can afford it, same with education, I totally utterly deeply reject that. By merit or limitation of resources, fine, but not by &quot;he who has the gold&quot;.<br>
<br>
Hm, America has run into such trouble because it's so powerful, but so naive and frankly hasn't had the utter ** kicked out of it and learned to eat humble pie like the rest of the world has, which leads to arrogance and a lack of empathy, like Britain in the late 1800s. Note this is a cultural overlook, not *a statement in regard to individual citizens*. Cultures change and mature, America is basically a youth, brash, powerful, but headstrong, with little sense of forethought. Capitolsim is good for solving immediate needs, but without damn good restraints or *willing co-operation*, long term its catastrophic.<br>
Examples include the butchery motor vehicles, tobacco and alcohol cause. The former is a real useful item, the later personal enjoyments, but between them they  havoc they caused makes the deaths suffered in wars puny. and NO ONE DOES anything because they are seen, designed and advertised   and have become ingrained in society due to retailing needs.<br>
I'm not sayuing they should be banned, lol  no. But that because folk were making fat profits from them, and good selling techniques, they have been taken far too lightly and the mega-deaths practically ignored.<br>
<br>
In a round about way, its about personable responsibility and morality, a good point someone pointed out in regard to an actual problem socialism doesnt solve. neither does Capitlosim, but capitolism exploits weaknesses.<br>
<br>
When the ice caps melt, when the oceans die, when giant hurricanes make living on the seaboard  impractical, what will we do?<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p>Redorious<br>
Archmage<br>
Karana<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=304331">Redorious, Everquest Archmage's profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:medium;">I'd rather be a Fool who believes in Dragons, Than a King who believes in Nothing</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.silverblades-suitcase.com">Silverblades Suitcase<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.silverblades-suitcase.com/artofadreamer/3d/excalibur2thumb.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caenn>Caenn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#333333>(1/27/03 4:42:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=80>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: idiot socialists</span><hr size=1> In response to Belarkan...<br>
<br>
As you can see by my low post count - six now? heh - I'm not one to chime in very often.  The only time I really do is when the issue is something about which I feel very strongly and think I have something to say that may add to the discussion.  Consequently, I tend to say things in the heat of passion.  <br>
<br>
However, while there are admittedly things in my last post I'd like to edit out, I frankly don't see the logic in many of your counterpoints.  In many cases your comments are too general to really qualify as good criticism, and in other cases you do some of the same things you criticise me for.<br>
<br>
Look, I don't mean to turn this into a &quot;why America is good/bad&quot; debate.  I use it as an example of functional capitalism because a) it is my largest frame of reference and b) like you said (and I agree with you), the US and capitalism are bound together.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Berlarkan: &quot;One would expect, from a wise Philosophy student like you surely are...&quot;<br>
<br>
Honestly, is the condescension really necessary?  I'm all for calling a turd a turd, but at least have the balls to come out and say what you really mean.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;Because, really, your whole post is more a claim of your absolut comfidence in the system than the fruit of deep thoughts.<br>
<br>
<br>
You dont even try to justify yourself  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->       &quot;<br>
<br>
My responses were general at best because I had so much I wanted to cover.  This is a message board for those of us addicted to a video game..not a dissertation, afterall.<br>
<br>
You've apparently failed to consider the possiblilty that my confidence in the system <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the fruit of deep thought.  Additionally, it is presumptuous of you to take my confidence in the free market system for an &quot;absolute confidence&quot; in the entire American governing system.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan:<br>
<br>
(quoting me)<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
&quot;society centered around the free market economy has made the United States of America (arguably) the most powerful nation that has ever existed at any time in history. And it's happened in a relative flash-in-the-pan of 200 or so years&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am grateful beyond words that we have leaders with the testicular fortitude to do what needs to be done to protect it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;that the true genious of the capitalistic system lies in the fact that it doesn't just accomodate this human trait, it wholly embraces it&quot;<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
&quot;Naivety appart, do you really buy that??&quot;<br>
<br>
In regards to the first statement you quoted, I cannot see where you could disagree. The only argument I can think of at 7am has to do with the context of the word &quot;powerful&quot;.  There is a reason that the United States is the one remaining super-power.  Please, tell me why I shouldn't &quot;buy that&quot;.<br>
<br>
In regards to the second quote, sappy (bleh) language aside my sentiment is the same.  And despite the fact that a very vocal minority in the US disagrees (the media eats it up), most of the country is in agreement, insofar as you can trust poll statistics.<br>
<br>
And the third point...well, once again I ask you explain to me where I'm wrong.  I would argue that if you disagree it is because you don't fully understand the concepts on which capitalism is based.  To me the explanation is self evident:  capitalisim works because people are competitive and greedy by nature and will always be so.  Governing systems and trade laws and wishful thinking cannot change that.  If you'd like I'll write a whole post on just this topic, but right now I want to respond to the rest of your post.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan:<br>
<br>
(quoting me)<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
&quot;I won't even get into the reasons for us doing what we're doing in Iraq, or what ties there may or may not be with Al Qaeda&quot;.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
&quot;Please, will you?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->       &quot;<br>
<br>
Sure...<br>
<br>
To begin with, we are still in a state of war with Iraq.  We just happen to be at armistice, or cease-fire if you'd like, something for which there are agreed-upon conditions.  Saddam Hussein has routinely broken the conditions of this armistice.  <br>
<br>
Just to cite a few examples: firing on US and British fighter planes patrolling the no-fly zone, actually downing one of our unmanned spy planes a few months back, selling oil that he's not allowed to sell to fund military assets that he's not supposed to have, kicking UN inspectors out of the country in the 90's after having made a farce of the inspection program, brutally crushing a Kurdish rebellion in 1998(?), etc.  The current inspection program is nearly as much of a farce as it was in the 90's, though this time Iraq is at least trying to fake compliance.  As I type, Hans Blix is addressing the United Nations.  He is reporting that he believes Iraq has had weapons in the recent past (in violation of UN sanctions) that they were not allowed to have and indeed may still have such weapons.<br>
<br>
That much is provable.  The rest is my opinion and is up for debate...<br>
<br>
This behavior, however, has been tolerated because the threat from Iraq was &quot;contained&quot; and the world turned its attention to, among other issues, the mess in Bosnia and later Kosovo.  Then 9-11 happened.  The United States is no longer so much concerned with containing or reacting to threat as it is with eliminating it outright.  9-11 was all the primer that was needed.  The government is attempting to change its long tradition of reaction to one of active pre-emption, hence the possibility of &quot;pre-emptive&quot; military action in Iraq.  <br>
<br>
I do not find it much of a stretch to think that a) Saddam Hussein would provide terrorists with training, weapons, funding...whatever they need, were he given the chance, and b) that terrorists know this and will try and make it happen.<br>
<br>
The US government claims to have proof that he possesses large quantities of VX nerve agent and the anthrax virus among others.  While I do not think that they would be stupid enough to lie about this, contrary to what you may think, I do think that it is necessary to present this proof to the world.  Members of the US left who were opposing military action on the grounds that there was no proof (Joe Lieberman, to name one) have since publicly reversed themselves after having supposedly been shown said evidence.<br>
<br>
The problem with making this evidence public at this point is that there are surely intelligence assets remaining in Iraq (i.e. people).  Obviously, this would include European as well as American personnel.  The release of such intelligence would necessarily expose these spies to the Iraqi government, which, in that regime, would certainly result in their execution.<br>
<br>
As for oil...the United States imports a relatively small portion of its oil from Iraq through the &quot;oil for food&quot; agreement (another farce).  I pay about $1.45 USD for a gallon of gas right now.  If all the oil wells in Iraq were to dry up tomorrow I imagine I would still be paying about $1.45 USD a gallon the day after.  The notion that we are bent on controlling all of Iraq's oil is just plain absurd.<br>
<br>
Additionally, if you honestly believe that the United States <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>wants</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to go to war, I just don't know what to tell you.  I am still on status to be called to active duty.  Do you really think I want to go off to a desert halfway around the world that I could wind up not coming back from?  Please.<br>
<br>
Enough on Iraq...we can get into that a bit more later on.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;Oh, before i forget, im 29, i live in france, i earn some decent money as a teacher...&quot;<br>
<br>
Good lord, this explains a lot.  I see teachers in France are reading the same books as teachers in the US.  What's scary is that you're teaching a whole generation of kids to think like you.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
As far as all of your quoted articles are concerned, the fact that you can surf the net and quote &quot;authorities&quot; on the far left of the left wing proves nothing to me.  If I cared to do so, I'm sure I could surf the net and find quotes from just as reputable ultra-right wing sources.  I'm not concerned with what you read, because I'm fairly confident that it's ALL you read.<br>
<br>
Though it is off subject, I feel it's relevent here.  I'm an atheist.  I always get a kick out of religious people who attempt to invoke biblical passages to reinforce their positions.  What you're doing here is no different.  The links and articles you posted were so biased (not to mention flat wrong) that they were not even laughable.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan:<br>
<br>
(quoting me)<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
&quot;...as fodder for some of the over-educated pseudo-intelligent types out there...&quot;<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
&quot;You certainly seem to think you are worth a damn IRL ?&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm not going to take the obvious shot here.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;1/ Economy is not governed by fate, like free market zealots would like to believe.Things can change, and will.&quot;<br>
<br>
Somehow I don't think I'd be far off in assuming that you're lumping me into the &quot;free market zealot&quot; crowd.  First of all, I absolutely do not believe anything close to this.  Free market <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>itself</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is not governed by fate.  Fate implies that there is some greater design.  <br>
<br>
To me, the fact that you believe this to be so means that either you do not truly understand the meaning of the word fate or, as I've already stated, that you do not truly understand the concept of capitalism.  In this case I believe it is the former.  <br>
<br>
Free market is governed by competition, which feeds directly off of the immediate wants and/or needs of the people.  It is therefore extremely ecclectic by nature.  Fate would imply that there is some greater plan or greater power at work shaping events to an end... i.e. socialism.  This is anything but the case where capitalism is concerned.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;As people realise its time to really limit free market before its too late (you know, those little things like global warming and world great poverty, beeing worse and worse every day, but hey isnt it destiny?  ), they are also conscious they will have to find a way and limit USA imperialism....because capitalism and USA are tied together.&quot;<br>
<br>
And you accuse ME of having &quot;blind faith&quot;?  Sheesh.  Blather like this just serves to erode your crediblility.<br>
<br>
And why is it that Europeans seem to think global warming is going to wipe us all out tomorrow?  I mean, I agree that it is a definate problem and must be addressed...but there is such as thing as <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">prioritizing!</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->  Have you heard the saying &quot;one step at a time&quot;?  Seriously, there are so many more immediate threats that need to be addressed.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;nor do we have to live forever sentenced to think, read, and sleep 09/11.&quot;<br>
<br>
I would be interested to hear how your opinion changes should (god forbid) something on the same scale happen in your country.  I agree that we cannot allow ourselves to be bound the events of 9-11 forever.  But at the same time, there are still people out there who, if given the opportunity, would take great pleasure in doing it again.  And until that threat is quelled, I don't believe we can safely let it go.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Ok, one more Iraq thing...<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;All this war will do is produce more terrorism and instability in an area where the balance is already weak.&quot;<br>
<br>
I've heard liberal anti-war types saying this in the US as well.  Can you please explain this to me?  It seems to be one of those common arguments that sounds really good but that nobody ever cares to substantiate.  I'm not saying I disagree necessarily, I'd just like to know your reasons for believing this to be true.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
And lastly...<br>
<br>
Belarkan: &quot;It isn't enough that you bring almost nothing to the debate, but you also feel the need to insult people, because belittle them is the only way for you to make a point:&quot;<br>
<br>
I love the irony here.  First you insult me, then you admonish me because you feel that I am insulting.<br>
<br>
/boggle<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
